INTRODUCTION
This project focuses on the development and study of the PIC16F877A microcontroller from Microchip Technology for learning and educational purposes.
The main objective of this project is to understand the fundamentals of embedded systems design, microcontroller programming, and PCB development. The system is divided into three stages:
Base Board â€“ Contains the minimum required components to operate the PIC16F877A microcontroller, such as power supply, crystal oscillator, and reset circuit.


Development Board â€“ Level 1 â€“ Includes basic interfacing components like LEDs, switches, and simple input/output devices for testing fundamental programs.


Development Board â€“ Level 2 â€“ Includes advanced peripherals such as LCD, sensors, communication modules, or ADC-based components for advanced experimentation.



====================================================================================================================
1)----> BASE BOARD - PCB
====================================================================================================================



BASE BOARD DESCRIPTION
The Base Board is designed to support the PIC16F877A (40-pin DIP) microcontroller with reliable power, clock, and programming capability.
Key Features
12V DC Input with onboard voltage regulator providing regulated 5V VCC and decoupling capacitors for stable operation.


ICSP interface compatible with PICkit 3 (MCLR/VPP, VDD, VSS, PGD, PGC) for programming and debugging.


External crystal oscillator connected to OSC1/OSC2 with load capacitors for accurate clock generation.


MCLR reset circuit with push-button and pull-up resistor.


Power indication LED for status monitoring.


Custom PCB layout with optimized routing, grounding, and accessible I/O header connections.


Objective
To provide a stable and expandable hardware platform for embedded system development using the PIC16F877A.
PCB Layer Stack and Bill of Materials (BOM)



